\begin_layout Section*
The Goal of the Paper
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With this background material understood, here's the abstract of the paper
 that my project is based on, which perfectly summarizes the goal of that
 work:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

We consider the problem of reproducing the performance of a stock market
 index, but without purchasing all of the stocks that make up the index,
 index tracking.
 We also consider the problem of outperforming the index, enhanced indexation.
 We present mixed-integer linear programming formulations of these problems.
 Our formulations include transaction costs, a constraint limiting the number
 of stocks that can be purchased and a limit on the total transaction cost
 that can be incurred.
 As our formulations of these problems are mixed-integer linear programs
 we can use a standard solver (Cplex).
 Numeric results are presented for eight data sets drawn from major markets.
 The largest of these data sets involves over 2000 stocks
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In particular, we want to create our own Tracking Portfolio (denoted TP)
 which is optimized with respect to some mixed-integer linear program.
 We use regression analysis in order to determine how successful our TP
 is.
 For instance, if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 represents the monthly return of the S&P 500 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 represents the monthly return of our TP, then the least squares regression
 line (where we are regressing the returns from the portfolio against the
 returns from the index) has the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y=\alpha+\beta X.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note here that if our TP perfectly tracks the index, then we would have
 a regression intercept (alpha) of zero, and a regression slope (beta) of
 one.
 Enhanced indexation (sometimes referred to as enhanced index tracking)
 aims to reproduce the performance of a stock market index, but to generate
 excess return (return over and above the return achieved by the index).
 One phrase often encountered with regard to enhanced indexation is ‘‘adding
 alpha”.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
thispagestyle{empty}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem Formulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now introduce notation which are used in the paper.
 We observe over time 
\begin_inset Formula $0,1,2,\dots,T$
\end_inset

 the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 stocks, as well as the index we are tracking.
 We are interested in deciding the best set of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 stocks to hold (where 
\begin_inset Formula $K\leq N$
\end_inset

), as well as their appropriate quantities.
 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varepsilon_{i} & =\text{ be the minimum proportion of the TP\text{ that must be held in stock \ensuremath{i} if any of the stock is held} }\\
\delta_{i} & =\text{ be the maximum proportion of the TP that can be held in stock \ensuremath{i} if any of the stock is held}\\
X_{i} & =\text{ be the number of units of stock \ensuremath{i} in the current TP}\\
V_{i,t} & =\text{ be the value (price) of one unit of stock \ensuremath{i} at time \ensuremath{t}}\\
I_{t} & =\text{ be the value of the index at time \ensuremath{t}}\\
R_{t} & =\text{ be the single period continuous time return for the index at time \ensuremath{t}, i.e. \ensuremath{R_{t}=\ln(I_{t}/I_{t-1})}}\\
r_{i,t} & =\text{ be the single period continuous time return for stock \ensuremath{i} at time \ensuremath{t}, i.e. \ensuremath{r_{i,t}=\ln(V_{i,t}/V_{i,t-1})}}\\
C & =\text{ the total value (\ensuremath{\geq0}) of the current TP at time \ensuremath{T}, i.e. \ensuremath{C=\sum_{i=1}^{n}X_{i}V_{i,T}} plus cash change ;}\\
f_{i}^{s} & =\text{ be the fractional cost of selling one unit of stock \ensuremath{i} at time \ensuremath{T}}\\
f_{i}^{b} & =\text{ be the fractional cost of buying one unit of stock \ensuremath{i} at time \ensuremath{T}}\\
\gamma & =\text{ be the limit \ensuremath{(0\leq\gamma\leq1)} on the proportion of \ensuremath{C} that can be consumed by transaction cost}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Decision Variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our decision variables are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x_{i} & =\text{ the number of units (\ensuremath{\geq0}) of stock \ensuremath{i} that we choose to hold in the new TP}\\
G_{i} & =\text{ the transaction cost (\ensuremath{\geq0}) incurred in selling/buying stock \ensuremath{i}}\\
z_{i} & =\text{ \ensuremath{=1} if any stock of \ensuremath{i} is held in the new TP, \ensuremath{=0} otherwise}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Without significant loss of generality (since the sums of money involved
 are large) we allow 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 to take fractional values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Constraints associated with index tracking problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The constraints associated with the index tracking problem are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sum_{i=1}^{N}z_{i}=K\label{eq:1}\\
\varepsilon_{i}z_{i}\leq x_{i}V_{i,T}\leq\delta_{i}z_{i} &  & 1\leq i\leq N\label{eq:2}\\
G_{i}\geq f_{i}^{s}(X_{i}-x_{i})V_{i,T} &  & 1\leq i\leq N\label{eq:3}\\
G_{i}\geq f_{i}^{b}(x_{i}-X_{i})V_{i,T} &  & 1\leq i\leq N\label{eq:4}\\
\sum_{i=1}^{N}G_{i}\leq\gamma C\label{eq:5}\\
\sum_{i=1}^{N}x_{i}V_{i,T}=C-\sum_{i=1}^{N}G_{i}\label{eq:6}\\
x_{i},G_{i}\geq0 &  & 1\leq i\leq N\label{eq:7}\\
z_{i}\in[0,1] &  & 1\leq i\leq N\label{eq:8}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Equation~(
\backslash
ref{eq:1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 ensures that there are exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 stocks in the new TP.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Equation~(
\backslash
ref{eq:2})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 ensures that if a stock 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is not in the new TP 
\begin_inset Formula $(z_{i}=0$
\end_inset

) then 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is also zero; it also ensures that if the stock is chosen to be in the
 new TP (
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}=1$
\end_inset

) then the amount of the stock held satisfies the proportion limits defined.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Equations~(
\backslash
ref{eq:3}) and (
\backslash
ref{eq:4})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 define the transaction cost and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Equation~(
\backslash
ref{eq:5})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 limits the total transaction cost incurred.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Equation~(
\backslash
ref{eq:6})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is a balance constraint such that the total value of the new TP at time
 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 equals the value of the current TP at time 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 plus the cash change (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

) minus the total transaction cost.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
thispagestyle{empty}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Index Tracking Objective
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Adopting the regression viewpoint for index tracking we have that ideally
 our TP would be chosen such that when we perform a regression of TP returns
 against index returns we would find that the regression line has an intercept
 (alpha) of zero, and a slope (beta) of one.
 However achieving this ideal is not straightforward.
 There are a number of complications to achieving this ideal within the
 context of a linear (or linearisable) formulation, as will become apparent
 below.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The single period continuous time return for the TP in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ln\left(\sum_{i=1}^{N}x_{i}V_{i,t}/\sum_{i=1}^{N}x_{i}V_{i,t-1}\right).
\]

\end_inset

This is a nonlinear function of the decision variables.
 In the paper, the authors show how to approximate this nonlinear function
 by a linear one; namely the (linear approximate) return for the TP in period
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{N}w_{i}r_{i,t}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i,t}$
\end_inset

 represents the return for stock 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and is given by the formula 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i,t}=\ln(V_{i,t}/V_{i,t-1})$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset

 represents the proportion invested in stock 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w_{i}=v_{i}x_{i}\qquad1\leq i\leq N\label{eq:9}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}=V_{i,T}/(C-\gamma C)$
\end_inset

 (see the Appendix for more details as to how this is done).
 Using the log-sum inequality it is possible to prove (assuming we spend
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma C$
\end_inset

 in transaction cost) that the average return from this approximation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{t=1}^{T}\sum_{i=1}^{N}w_{i}r_{i.t}/T
\]

\end_inset

 over-estimates average tracking portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{t=1}^{T}\ln\left(\sum_{i=1}^{N}x_{i}V_{i,t}/\sum_{i=1}^{N}x_{i}V_{i,t-1}\right)/T
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we regress these TP returns from standard regression theory that the
 ordinary least-squares estimates, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\beta}$
\end_inset

, for the intercept and slope of the regression line are given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\alpha & =\sum_{i=1}^{N}w_{i}\alpha_{i}\label{eq:10}\\
\beta & =\sum_{i=1}^{N}w_{i}\beta_{i}\label{eq:11}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the ordinary least-squares regression intercept and slope when we regress
 the returns from stock 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i,t}$
\end_inset

) against the index returns (
\begin_inset Formula $R_{t}$
\end_inset

).
 Ideally we would like, for index tracking, to choose 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 stocks and their associated quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq N$
\end_inset

 such that we achieve 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1$
\end_inset

.
 For real life data this may not, however, be achievable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
thispagestyle{empty}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Mixed-Integer Linear Program
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to acheive this, the authors adopted a two stage approach: where
 the primary objective is to achieve the desired slope of one and the secondary
 objective is to achieve the desired intercept of zero, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{first minimize }|\alpha|\text{ and then minimize }|\beta-1|.\label{eq:milp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The modulus objectives above are not linear, however there is a standard
 way to linearize them: introduce variables 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
D & \geq\alpha\label{eq:12}\\
D & \geq-\alpha\label{eq:1-1}\\
E & \geq\beta-1\label{eq:14}\\
E & \geq-(\beta-1)\label{eq:15}\\
D,E & \geq0\label{eq:16}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Then the full MILP formulation for solving the index tracking problem in
 the first-stage (primary objective to achieve the desired intercept of
 zero) is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{minimize } & D\\
\text{subject to } & \text{Equations 1-11 and 13-17}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We then set 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\alpha^{\mathrm{opt}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{\mathrm{opt}}$
\end_inset

 is the optimal intercept produced in stage-one.
 Then in the second-stage we
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{minimize } & E\\
\text{subject to } & \text{Equations 1-11, 13-17}\\
 & \,\alpha=\alpha^{\mathrm{opt}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We will use MATLAB to solve this MILP.
 Before we begin, we want create a MATLAB which we will useful in what follows.
 The function is denoted 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

function [C, a, b, v] = TrackingPortfolio(I,V, X, cash, gamma)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and the code is given below.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}=(v_{1},\dots,v_{N})^{\top}$
\end_inset

 is the vector with 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}=V_{i,T}/(C-\gamma C)$
\end_inset

.
 We also have 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}=(a_{1},\dots,a_{N})^{\top}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}=(b_{1},\dots,b_{N})^{\top}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}=\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}=\beta_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the ordinary least-squares regression intercept and slope when we regress
 the returns 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{i}$
\end_inset

 from stock 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 against the returns 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}$
\end_inset

 of the index.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha=\sum_{i=1}^{N}a_{i}v_{i}x_{i}\quad\text{and}\quad\beta=\sum_{i=1}^{N}b_{i}v_{i}x_{i},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Tabular
<lyxtabular version="3" rows="1" columns="1">
<features tabularvalignment="middle">
<column alignment="center" valignment="top">
<row>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

function [C,a,b,v] = TrackingPortfolio(I,V,X,cash,gamma)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

sz = size(V); N = sz(1); T = sz(2); Vf = V(:,T); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

R = zeros(1,T-1); r = zeros(N,T-1); a = zeros(N,1); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

b = zeros(N,1); v = zeros(N,1); p = zeros(N,2);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

C = dot(X,Vf) + cash; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

for t = 1:T-1        
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

    R(1,t) = log(I(t+1)/I(t));
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

end; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

for i = 1:N     
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

      for t = 1:T-1         
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

         r(i,t) = log(V(i,t+1)/V(i,t));     
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

      end; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

end; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

for i=1:N     
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

   p(i,:) = polyfit(R,r(i,:),1);  
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

   a(i) = p(i,2);     
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

   b(i) = p(i,1);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

   v(i) = Vf(i)/(C-gamma*C);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

end; 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
</lyxtabular>

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
thispagestyle{empty}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The following example will help clarify all of the concepts we discuss.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{I}=(I_{0},I_{1},\dots,I_{12})^{\top}$
\end_inset

 be the vector where the component 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{t}$
\end_inset

 denotes the value of the S&P 500 at the end of month 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 corresponds to Dec 2020, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

 corresponds to Jan 2021, and so on...).
 Thus the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{I}$
\end_inset

 is given (rounding to the nearest integer) by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{I}=(3756,3714,3811,3973,4181,4204,4298,4395,4523,4308,4605,4567,4766)^{\top}.
\]

\end_inset

Next let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}=(R_{1},\dots,R_{12})^{\top}$
\end_inset

 be the vector where the component 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{t}$
\end_inset

 denotes the single period time return fo the S&P 500 at the end of month
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

 corresponds to Jan 2021, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=2$
\end_inset

 corresponds to Feb 2021, and so on...).
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{t}=\ln(I_{t}/I_{t-1})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}$
\end_inset

 is given (rounding to the fourth decimal place) by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{R}=(-0.0112,0.0258,0.0416,0.0510,0.0055,0.0221,0.0223,0.0287,-0.0487,0.0667,-0.0083,0.0427)^{\top}.
\]

\end_inset

Below is the graph of the S&P500 during 2021:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename SP500.jpg
	lyxscale 30
	scale 30

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For instance, we see that the S&P 500 did poorly in the month of September.
 This corresopnds to the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{9}=-0.0487$
\end_inset

.
 Next, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{V}_{i}=(V_{i,0},V_{i,1},\dots,V_{i,12})^{\top}$
\end_inset

 be the vector where the component 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i,t}$
\end_inset

 denotes the value of one share of stock 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1$
\end_inset

 corresponds to Amazon , 
\begin_inset Formula $i=2$
\end_inset

 corresponds to Facebook, and 
\begin_inset Formula $i=3$
\end_inset

 corresponds to Apple) at the end of month 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{i}=(r_{i,1},\dots,r_{i,12})$
\end_inset

 be the vector where the the component 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i,t}$
\end_inset

 denotes the single period time return for stock 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 at the end of month 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

 corresponds to Jan 2021, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=2$
\end_inset

 corresponds to Feb 2021, and so on...).
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i,t}=\ln(V_{i,t}/V_{i,t-1})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{V}_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{V}_{2}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{V}_{3}$
\end_inset

 are given (rounding to the nearest integer) by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{V}_{1} & =(3257,3206,3093,3094,3467,3223,3440,3328,3471,3285,3372,3507,3304)^{\top}\\
\boldsymbol{V}_{2} & =(273,259,258,295,325,329,348,356,379,339,323,324,335)^{\top}.\\
\boldsymbol{V}_{3} & =(133,132,121,122,131,125,137,146,152,141,150,165,178)^{\top}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{X}=(X_{1},X_{2},X_{3})^{\top}$
\end_inset

 be the vector where 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 denotes number of shares of stock 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in the current TP.
 We will assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{X}=(10,50,100)^{\top}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=0.9$
\end_inset

 and suppose we have 
\begin_inset Formula $1000$
\end_inset

 dollars in cash change.
 In Matlab, we write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


