\begin_layout Section*
Solving the First-Stage MILP using MATLAB
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now want to solve the first-stage MILP using MATLAB.
 However in our approach, we shall ignore the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}^{s}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}^{b}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq N$
\end_inset

, There reason is that, unlike in past (like when the paper was written),
 most trading is commission-free these days.
 Most brokers make their revenue through a process called 
\series bold
payment for order flow 
\series default
(which is itself considered controversial).
 Thus we will not need to worry about transaction costs when optimizing
 our TP.
 Note however that we still keep 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\gamma)C$
\end_inset

 represents the amount we are willing to invest in our new TP).
 With this in mind, the first-stage MILP we wish to solve is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{minimize} & \quad D\nonumber \\
\text{subject to} & \quad\sum_{i=1}^{N}a_{i}v_{i}x_{i}\leq D\nonumber \\
 & \quad-\sum_{i=1}^{N}a_{i}v_{i}x_{i}\leq D\nonumber \\
 & \quad\sum_{i=1}^{N}b_{i}v_{i}x_{i}-1\leq E\nonumber \\
 & \quad1-\sum_{i=1}^{N}b_{i}v_{i}x_{i}\leq E\label{eq:MILP1}\\
 & \quad\varepsilon_{i}z_{i}\leq(V_{i,T}/C)x_{i}\leq\delta_{i}z_{i} & 1\leq i\leq N\nonumber \\
 & \quad\sum_{i=1}^{N}v_{i}x_{i}=1\nonumber \\
 & \quad\sum_{i=1}^{N}z_{i}=K\nonumber \\
 & \quad x_{i},D,E\geq0 & 1\leq i\leq N\nonumber \\
 & \quad z_{i}\in\{0,1\} & 1\leq i\leq N\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

We will find an optimal solution to this MILP problem using MATLAB, which
 has a built-in function whose purpose is to solve MILP problems like this.
 The syntax for this function is 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

x = intlinprog(c,intcon,Ain,bin,Aeq,beq,lb,ub)
\end_layout

\end_inset

, where the MILP solver assumes that the MILP has the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{minimize} & \quad\boldsymbol{c}^{\top}\boldsymbol{x}\\
\text{subject to} & \quad A_{\mathrm{in}}\boldsymbol{x}\leq\boldsymbol{b}_{\mathrm{in}}\\
 & \quad A_{\mathrm{eq}}\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{b}_{eq}\\
 & \quad\boldsymbol{lb}\leq\boldsymbol{x}\leq\boldsymbol{ub}\\
 & \quad\boldsymbol{x}(\mathrm{intcon})\text{ are integers}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{intcon}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{\mathrm{in}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{\mathrm{eq}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{lb}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{ub}$
\end_inset

 are vectors.
 In order to use this function, we need to convert our MILP into this form.
 First let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{1},\dots,x_{N},x_{N+1},\dots,x_{2N},x_{2N+1},x_{2N+2})^{\top}=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n},z_{1},\dots,z_{n},D,E)^{\top},
\]

\end_inset

and similarly let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}^{\top}=(0,\dots,0,1,0)^{\top}\in\mathbb{R}^{2N+2}$
\end_inset

 is the vector with 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq2N$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2N+1}=1$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2N+2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Ths 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}^{\top}\boldsymbol{x}=D$
\end_inset

 is our objective function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{intcon}=(N+1,N+2,\dots,2N)^{\top}\in\mathbb{R}^{N}$
\end_inset

 (this tells us that the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{N+1},x_{N+2},\dots,x_{2N}$
\end_inset

 are integers).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{lb}=(0,\dots,0)^{\top}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{lb}\in\mathbb{R}^{2N+2}$
\end_inset

 (this tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\geq0$
\end_inset

), and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{ub}=(\mathrm{Inf},\dots,\mathrm{Inf},1,\dots,1,\mathrm{Inf},\mathrm{Inf})\in\mathbb{R}^{2N+2}$
\end_inset

, that is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(ub)_{i}=\begin{cases}
\infty & \text{if }1\leq i\leq N\\
1 & \text{if }N+1\leq i\leq2N\\
\infty & \text{if }i=2N+1\\
\infty & \text{if }i=2N+2.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

This tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i},x_{2N+1},x_{2N+2}\leq\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{N+i}\leq1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq N$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, since 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{N+i}\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{N+i}\in\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq N$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{lb}\leq\boldsymbol{x}\leq\boldsymbol{ub}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}(\mathrm{intcon)}$
\end_inset

 are integers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next, let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{\mathrm{eq}}=\begin{pmatrix}v_{1} & \cdots & v_{N} & 0 & \cdots & 0 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \cdots & 0 & 1 & \cdots & 1 & 0 & 0
\end{pmatrix}\quad\text{and}\quad\boldsymbol{b}_{\mathrm{eq}}=\begin{pmatrix}1\\
K
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathrm{eq}}\in\mathbb{R}^{2\times(2N+2)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{\mathrm{eq}}\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{\mathrm{in}}^{1}=\begin{pmatrix}a_{1}v_{1} & \cdots & a_{N}v_{N} & 0 & \cdots & 0 & -1 & 0\\
-a_{1}v_{1} & \cdots & -a_{N}v_{N} & 0 & \cdots & 0 & -1 & 0\\
b_{1}v_{1} & \cdots & b_{N}v_{N} & 0 & \cdots & 0 & 0 & -1\\
-b_{1}v_{1} & \cdots & -b_{N}v_{N} & 0 & \cdots & 0 & 0 & -1
\end{pmatrix}\quad\text{and}\quad\boldsymbol{b}_{\mathrm{in}}^{1}=\begin{pmatrix}0\\
0\\
1\\
-1
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathrm{in}}^{1}\in\mathbb{R}^{4\times(2N+2)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{\mathrm{in}}^{1}\in\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

.
 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{\mathrm{in}}^{2}=\begin{pmatrix}(1-\gamma)v_{1} &  & 0 & -\delta_{1} &  & 0 & 0 & 0\\
 & \ddots &  &  & \ddots &  & \vdots & \vdots\\
0 &  & (1-\gamma)v_{n} & 0 &  & -\delta_{N} & 0 & 0
\end{pmatrix}\quad\text{and}\quad\boldsymbol{b}_{\mathrm{in}}^{2}=\begin{pmatrix}0\\
\vdots\\
0
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathrm{in}}^{2}\in\mathbb{R}^{N\times(2N+2)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{\mathrm{in}}^{2}\in\mathbb{R}^{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{\mathrm{in}}^{3}=\begin{pmatrix}(\gamma-1)v_{1} &  & 0 & \varepsilon_{1} &  & 0 & 0 & 0\\
 & \ddots &  &  & \ddots &  & \vdots & \vdots\\
0 &  & (\gamma-1)v_{n} & 0 &  & \varepsilon_{N} & 0 & 0
\end{pmatrix}\quad\text{and}\quad\boldsymbol{b}_{\mathrm{in}}^{3}=\begin{pmatrix}0\\
\vdots\\
0
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathrm{in}}^{3}\in\mathbb{R}^{N\times(2N+2)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{\mathrm{in}}^{3}\in\mathbb{R}^{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Let
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{\mathrm{in}}=\begin{pmatrix}A_{\mathrm{in}}^{1}\\
A_{\mathrm{in}}^{2}\\
A_{\mathrm{in}}^{3}
\end{pmatrix}\quad\text{and}\quad\boldsymbol{b}_{\mathrm{in}}=\begin{pmatrix}\boldsymbol{b}_{\mathrm{in}}^{1}\\
\boldsymbol{b}_{\mathrm{in}}^{2}\\
\boldsymbol{b}_{\mathrm{in}}^{3}
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathrm{in}}\in\mathbb{R}^{(2N+4)\times(2N+2)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{\mathrm{in}}\in\mathbb{R}^{2N+4}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, we can rewrite 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:MILP1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{minimize} & \quad\boldsymbol{c}^{\top}\boldsymbol{x}\nonumber \\
\text{subject to} & \quad A_{\mathrm{in}}\boldsymbol{x}\leq\boldsymbol{b}_{\mathrm{in}}\nonumber \\
 & \quad A_{\mathrm{eq}}\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{b}_{eq}\label{eq:MILP2}\\
 & \quad\boldsymbol{lb}\leq\boldsymbol{x}\leq\boldsymbol{ub}\nonumber \\
 & \quad\boldsymbol{x}(\mathrm{intcon})\text{ are integers}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

which is the desired form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
thispagestyle{empty}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
MinimizeAlpha Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We create a MATLAB function denoted 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

function [x,alpha] = MinimizeAlpha(I, V, X, cash, gamma, epsilon, delta,
 K)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 whose code is given below.
 This function solves the MILP 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:MILP2})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and returns the optimal solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 together with together with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\alpha^{\mathrm{opt}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Tabular
<lyxtabular version="3" rows="1" columns="1">
<features tabularvalignment="middle">
<column alignment="center" valignment="top">
<row>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

function [x,alpha] = MinimizeAlpha(I,V,X,cash,gamma,epsilon,delta,K);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

[C,a,b,v] = TrackingPortfolio(I, V, X, cash , gamma);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

N = length(v);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

c = [zeros(2*N,1);1;0];
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Aeq = [v' , zeros(1,N+2) ; zeros(1,N), ones(1,N), 0, 0]; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

beq = [1; K]; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Ain1 = [(a.*v)', zeros(1,N), -1, 0;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

-(a.*v)', zeros(1,N), -1,0;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(b.*v)', zeros(1,N), 0,1;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

-(b.*v)', zeros(1,N), 0,-1];
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Ain2 = [diag((1-gamma)*v), diag(-delta), zeros(N,2)];
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Ain3 = [diag((gamma-1)*v), diag(epsilon), zeros(N,2)];
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Ain = [Ain1; Ain2; Ain3];
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

bin = [0;0;1;-1;zeros(2*N,1)];
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

intcon = N+1:2*N;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

intcon = intcon'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

lb = [zeros(2*N+2,1)];
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

ub = [Inf(N,1); ones(N,1) ; Inf; Inf];
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

[x,D] = intlinprog(c,intcon,Ain,bin,Aeq,beq,lb,ub);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

alpha = dot((a.*v),x(1:N)); 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
</lyxtabular>

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


