\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 If we set 
\begin_inset Formula $K=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}=(0;0;0)^{\top}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\delta}=(1;1;1)^{\top}$
\end_inset

, then we should expect our program to tell us that holding shares in Apple
 is the optimal solution since 
\begin_inset Formula $|a_{3}|=0.005$
\end_inset

 is optimal (we have 
\begin_inset Formula $|a_{1}|=0.013$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|a_{2}|=0.009$
\end_inset

, and clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $|a_{3}|<|a_{1}|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|a_{3}|<|a_{2}|$
\end_inset

).
 In MATLAB, we write
\end_layout

